# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vimscript-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] From July 2006 until September 2021, Moolenaar was employed by Google, working in the Zürich office on Google Calendar.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] He spent part of his time maintaining Vim.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Moolenaar was born in Lisse, Netherlands, in 1961.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] In 1985, he graduated from the Delft University of Technology with a degree in electrical engineering.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] In 1988, Moolenaar purchased an Amiga computer.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Familiar with vi, which had not been ported to the Amiga at the time, he tested several clones of vi, including Stevie.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Moolenaar took the source code of Stevie and improved upon it.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Seeking to match vi, Moolenaar eventually added in additional features, such as undoing multiple levels.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] The first version of "Vi IMitation" was released in 1992 on a public domain disk set made by Fred Fish.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Several users ported Vim onto other platforms, such as MS-DOS and Unix.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] In version 1.22 in 1992, Vi IMitation was renamed to "Vi IMproved".
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Vim is open-source and charityware; users are encouraged to donate to ICCF Holland.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] A number of other applications have been licensed this way since Vim's inception.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Vim has won several awards and has been referred to as one of the most popular text editors.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Other software tools that Moolenaar developed include a software build tool written in Python, called A-A-P, which is similar to make, and a programming language called Zimbu which puts an emphasis on readability of programs.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Moolenaar was a member of the Dutch Unix user group, NLUUG, which presented him with an award during its 25th anniversary, for his creation of Vim and his contributions to open-source software in general.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Moolenaar was an advocate of ICCF Holland, a non-governmental organization based in Kibaale, Uganda which he founded to support children whose parents have died of AIDS.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] In 1994, he volunteered as a water and sanitation engineer for the Kibaale Children's Centre; he made several return trips over the following twenty-five years.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] An estimated US$2,000 was raised for ICCF Holland in 1997, followed by US$4,000 a year later.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] In 1999, donation income totaled approximately US$7,000.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] He last visited the Kibaale Community Centre in 2020 before the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Following Bram's passing in 2023, ICCF Holland transferred all activities to its sister charity Kuwasha in Canada and dissolved at the end of 2025.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Moolenaar reported health problems in October 2022.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] On 5 August 2023, Moolenaar's family announced in the Vim Google Group that Moolenaar had died two days prior, at the age of 62, because of a rapidly developing medical condition.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] His funeral was held in Lisse, Netherlands, on 16 August 2023.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Vim was continued by co-contributor Christian Brabandt.
[src:vimscript-deep/bram-moolenaar] Bram Moolenaar was posthumously awarded the 2024 European SFS Award at SFSCON 24, a free software meeting organised since 2004 by the Free Software Foundation Europe (FSFE) and the Linux User Group Bolzano-Bozen (LUGBZ).
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:vimscript-deep/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] In computer science, **extensible programming** is a style of computer programming that focuses on mechanisms to extend the programming language, compiler, and runtime system (environment).
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Extensible programming languages, supporting this style of programming, were an active area of work in the 1960s, but the movement was marginalized in the 1970s.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Extensible programming has become a topic of renewed interest in the 21st century.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The first paper usually associated with the extensible programming language movement is M.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Douglas McIlroy's 1960 paper on macros for high-level programming languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Another early description of the principle of extensibility occurs in Brooker and Morris's 1960 paper on the compiler-compiler.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The peak of the movement was marked by two academic symposia, in 1969 and 1971.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] By 1975, a survey article on the movement by Thomas A.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The Forth was an exception, but it went essentially unnoticed.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] As typically envisioned, an extensible language consisted of a base language providing elementary computing facilities, and a metalanguage able to modify the base language.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] A program then consisted of metalanguage modifications and code in the modified base language.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The most prominent language-extension technique used in the movement was macro definition.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Grammar modification was also closely associated with the movement, resulting in the eventual development of adaptive grammar formalisms.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] At the 1969 conference, Simula was presented as an extensible language.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Standish described three classes of language extension, which he named *paraphrase*, *orthophrase*, and *metaphrase* (otherwise paraphrase and metaphrase being translation terms).
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Standish attributed the failure of the extensibility movement to the difficulty of programming successive extensions.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] A programmer might build a first shell of macros around a base language.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Then, if a second shell of macros is built around that, any subsequent programmer must be intimately familiar with both the base language, and the first shell.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] A third shell would require familiarity with the base and both the first and second shells, and so on.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Shielding a programmer from lower-level details is the intent of the abstraction movement that supplanted the extensibility movement.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Despite the earlier presentation of Simula as extensible, by 1975, Standish's survey does not seem in practice to have included the newer abstraction-based technologies (though he used a very general definition of extensibility that technically could have included them).
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] A 1978 history of programming abstraction from the invention of the computer until then, made no mention of macros, and gave no hint that the extensible languages movement had ever occurred.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Macros were tentatively admitted into the abstraction movement by the late 1980s (perhaps due to the advent of hygienic macros), by being granted the pseudonym *syntactic abstractions*.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] In the modern sense, a system that supports extensible programming will provide *all* of the features described below.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] This simply means that the source language(s) to be compiled must not be closed, fixed, or static.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] It must be possible to add new keywords, concepts, and structures to the source language(s).
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Languages which allow the addition of constructs with user defined syntax include Rocq, Racket, Camlp4, OpenC++, Seed7, Red, Rebol, and Felix.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] While it is acceptable for some fundamental and intrinsic language features to be immutable, the system must not rely solely on those language features.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] In extensible programming, a compiler is not a monolithic program that converts source code input into binary executable output.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The compiler itself must be extensible to the point that it is really a collection of plugins that assist with the translation of source language input into *anything*.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] For example, an extensible compiler will support the generation of object code, code documentation, re-formatted source code, or any other desired output.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The architecture of the compiler must permit its users to "get inside" the compilation process and provide alternative processing tasks at every reasonable step in the compilation process.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] At runtime, extensible programming systems must permit languages to extend the set of operations that it permits.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] For example, if the system uses a byte-code interpreter, it must allow new byte-code values to be defined.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] As with extensible syntax, it is acceptable for there to be some (smallish) set of fundamental or intrinsic operations that are immutable.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] However, it must be possible to overload or augment those intrinsic operations so that new or additional behavior can be supported.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Extensible programming systems should regard programs as data to be processed.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Those programs should be completely devoid of any kind of formatting information.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The visual display and editing of programs to users should be a translation function, supported by the extensible compiler, that translates the program data into forms more suitable for viewing or editing.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Naturally, this should be a two-way translation.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] This is important because it must be possible to easily process extensible programs in a *variety* of ways.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] It is unacceptable for the only uses of source language input to be editing, viewing and translation to machine code.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The arbitrary processing of programs is facilitated by de-coupling the source input from specifications of how it should be processed (formatted, stored, displayed, edited, etc.).
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Extensible programming systems must support the debugging of programs using the constructs of the original source language regardless of the extensions or transformation the program has undergone in order to make it executable.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] Most notably, it cannot be assumed that the only way to display runtime data is in *structures* or *arrays*.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] The debugger, or more correctly 'program inspector', must permit the display of runtime data in forms suitable to the source language.
[src:vimscript-deep/extensible-programming] For example, if the language supports a data structure for a business process or work flow, it must be possible for the debugger to display that data structure as a fishbone chart or other form provided by a plugin.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:vimscript-deep/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] A **text editor** is interactive software that allows a user to edit plain text, such as Notepad.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] As source code is text, any text editor can be used to edit code, but a source-code editor is designed with features specifically intended for editing code.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some provide integration with software development tools and provide a debugging environment.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] There are important differences between plain text (created and edited by text editors) and rich text (such as that created by word processors or desktop publishing software).
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Plain text exclusively consists of character representation.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Each character is represented by a fixed-length sequence of one, two, or four bytes, or as a variable-length sequence of one to four bytes, in accordance to specific character encoding conventions, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 2022, Shift JIS, UTF-8, or UTF-16.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] These conventions define many printable characters, but also non-printing characters that control the flow of the text, such as space, line break, and page break.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Plain text contains no other information about the text itself, not even the character encoding convention employed.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Plain text is stored in text files, although text files do not exclusively store plain text.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Since the early days of computers, plain text was (once by necessity and now by convention) generally displayed using a monospaced font, such that horizontal alignment and columnar formatting were sometimes done using whitespace characters.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Rich text can be saved in binary format (e.g.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] DOC), text files adhering to a markup language (e.g.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] RTF or HTML), or in a hybrid form of both (e.g.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Text editors are intended to open and save text files containing either plain text or anything that can be interpreted as plain text, including the markup for rich text or the markup for something else (e.g.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Before text editors existed, computer text was punched into cards with keypunch machines.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Physical boxes of these thin cardboard cards were then inserted into a card reader.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Magnetic tape, drum and disk card image files created from such card decks often had no line-separation characters at all, and assumed fixed-length 80- or 90-character records.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] An alternative to cards was Punched tape.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] It could be created by some teleprinters (such as the Teletype), which used special characters to indicate ends of records.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some early operating systems included batch text editors, either integrated with language processors or as separate utility programs; one early example was the ability to edit SQUOZE source files for SCAT in the SHARE Operating System.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The first interactive text editors were "line editors" oriented to teletypes: teleprinter-style or typewriter-style terminals that mechanically printed both input and output on the same continuous roll of paper, without an illuminated display.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Commands (often a single keystroke) effected edits to a file at an insertion point, that the operator needed to keep track of, called the "cursor".
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Edits were verified by typing a command to print a small section of the file, and periodically by printing the entire file.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] In some line editors, the cursor could be moved by commands that specified the line number in the file, text strings (context) for which to search, and eventually regular expressions.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Line editors were major improvements over keypunching.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some line editors could be used by keypunch; editing commands could be taken from a deck of cards and applied to a specified file.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some common line editors supported a "verify" mode in which change commands displayed the altered lines.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] An example configuration, circa 1975, was a Teletype Model 33 as a console to a PDP-11 using Version 6 Unix, manipulating text with the *ed*, the standard UNIX text editor.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] When computer terminals with video screens became available, screen-based text editors (sometimes called just "screen editors") became common.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] One of the earliest full-screen editors was O26, which was written for the operator console of the CDC 6000 series computers in 1967.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Another early full-screen editor was vi.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Written in the 1970s, it is still a standard editor on Unix and Linux operating systems.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Also written in the 1970s was the UCSD Pascal Screen Oriented Editor, which was optimized both for indented source code and general text.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Emacs, one of the first free and open-source software projects, is another early full-screen or real-time editor, one that was ported to many systems.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The 1977 Commodore PET was the first mass-market computer to feature a full-screen editor.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] A full-screen editor's ease-of-use and speed (compared to the line-based editors) motivated many early purchases of video terminals.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The core data structure in a text editor is the one that manages the string (sequence of characters) or list of records that represents the current state of the file being edited.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] While the former could be stored in a single long consecutive array of characters, the desire for text editors that could more quickly insert text, delete text, and undo/redo previous edits led to the development of more complicated sequence data structures.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] A typical text editor uses a gap buffer, a linked list of lines (as in PaperClip), a piece table, or a rope, as its sequence data structure.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some text editors are small and simple, while others offer broad and complex functions.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] For example, Unix and Unix-like operating systems have the pico editor (or a variant), but many also include the vi and Emacs editors.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Microsoft Windows systems come with the simple Notepad, though many people—especially programmers—prefer other editors with more features.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Under Apple Macintosh's classic Mac OS there was the native TeachText later replaced by SimpleText in 1994, which was replaced in Mac OS X by TextEdit, which combines features of a text editor with those typical of a word processor such as rulers, margins and multiple font selection.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] These features are not available simultaneously, but must be switched by user command, or through the program automatically determining the file type.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Most word processors can read and write files in plain text format, allowing them to open files saved from text editors.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Saving these files from a word processor, however, requires ensuring the file is written in plain text format, and that any text encoding or BOM settings will not obscure the file for its intended use.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Non-WYSIWYG word processors, such as WordStar, are more easily pressed into service as text editors, and in fact were commonly used as such during the 1980s.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The default file format of these word processors often resembles a markup language, with the basic format being plain text and visual formatting achieved using non-printing control characters or escape sequences.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Later word processors like Microsoft Word store their files in a binary format and are almost never used to edit plain text files.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some text editors can edit unusually large files such as log files or an entire database placed in a single file.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Simpler text editors may just read files into the computer's main memory.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] With larger files, this may be a slow process, and the entire file may not fit.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some text editors do not let the user start editing until this read-in is complete.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Editing performance also often suffers in nonspecialized editors, with the editor taking seconds or even minutes to respond to keystrokes or navigation commands.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Specialized editors have optimizations such as only storing the visible portion of large files in memory, improving editing performance.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some editors are programmable, meaning, e.g., they can be customized for specific uses.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] With a programmable editor it is easy to automate repetitive tasks or, add new functionality or even implement a new application within the framework of the editor.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] One common motive for customizing is to make a text editor use the commands of another text editor with which the user is more familiar, or to duplicate missing functionality the user has come to depend on.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Software developers often use editor customizations tailored to the programming language or development environment they are working in.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Emacs can even be programmed to emulate Vi, its rival in the traditional editor wars of Unix culture.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] An important group of programmable editors uses REXX as a scripting language.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] These "orthodox editors" contain a "command line" into which commands and macros can be typed and text lines into which line commands and macros can be typed.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Most such editors are derivatives of ISPF/PDF EDIT or of XEDIT, IBM's flagship editor for VM/SP through z/VM.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Among them are THE, KEDIT, X2, Uni-edit, and SEDIT.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] A text editor written or customized for a specific use can determine what the user is editing and assist the user, often by completing programming terms and showing tooltips with relevant documentation.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Many text editors for software developers include source code syntax highlighting and automatic indentation to make programs easier to read and write.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Programming editors often let the user select the name of an include file, function or variable, then jump to its definition.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some also allow for easy navigation back to the original section of code by storing the initial cursor location or by displaying the requested definition in a popup window or temporary buffer.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some editors implement this ability themselves, but often an auxiliary utility like ctags is used to locate the definitions.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Most text editors provide methods to duplicate and move text within the file, or between files.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Cut, copy and paste are often integrated with a system clipboard.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Text editors provide extensive facilities for searching and replacing strings of text, either individually, or groups of files in opened tabs or a selected folder.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] , and listing multiple results in one place.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Often—especially with older text editors—there is only one level of edit history remembered and successively issuing the undo command will only "toggle" the last change.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Modern or more complex editors usually provide a multiple-level history such that issuing the undo command repeatedly will revert the document to successively older edits.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] A separate redo command will cycle the edits "forward" toward the most recent changes.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Ability to jump to a specified line number.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] To define new commands or features as combinations of prior commands or other macros, perhaps with passed parameters, or with nesting of macros.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] To retain options set by the user between editing session.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] With names specified in, e.g., environment, profile, executed automatically at the beginning of an edit session or when opening a new file.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The ability to display multiple views of the same file, with independent cursor tracking, synchronizing changes among the windows but providing the same facilities as are available for independent files.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The ability to temporarily exclude sections of the text from view.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The ability to alter or insert data at a particular column, or to shift data to specific columns.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Reading or merging the contents of another text file into the file currently being edited.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Also, a case-shifting feature could translate to lowercase or uppercase.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some advanced text editors allow the editor to send all or sections of the file being edited to another utility and read the result back into the file in place of the lines being "filtered".
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] and other text that appears in an organized or predictable format.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Editors generally allow users to customize the colors or styles used for each language element.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] after one press navigated to the end of an on-screen row of text.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] typically have dedicated cursor movement keys, as do keyboards on personal computers.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] , have a dedicated field on the screen for entering commands as opposed to text.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Depending on the editor, the user may have to use cursor keys to switch between the command and text fields or the editor may interpret, e.g., specific function keys, as requests to switch.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] (also known as prefix commands or sequence commands) Some editors treat a file as an array of text lines with associated line numbers or sequence numbers, and have a distinct line number field for each text field.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Some editors also support line macros, also known as prefix macros or sequence macros.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] , some editors allow the sequence field to appear after the text field.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Text editors with additional functionality to facilitate the production of source code.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Includes so-called "orthodox editors" that are derivatives of Xedit.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Editors that implement folding without programing-specific features are usually called outliners (see below).
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Folding can be considered a specialized form of outlining.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Designed to manage and streamline large programming projects.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] They are usually only used for programming as they contain many features unnecessary for simple text editing.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] that are assembled by the software controlling the site and do not compose a complete HTML document.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] Allows multiple users to work on the same document simultaneously from remote locations over a network.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] The changes made by individual users are tracked and merged into the document automatically to eliminate the possibility of conflicting edits.
[src:vimscript-deep/text-editor] , are targeted at a single programming language.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim's documentation describes it as an improved form of the older vi text editor (though it is built from a distinct codebase).
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] In release information, the author originally implied that Vim was an abbreviation for "Vi IMitation", but later, the expansion was changed to "Vi IMproved" because, as described by the author, the functionality had increased beyond that of a clone of vi.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Some sources indicate the change happened with v2.0, but conflicting information (including from author) suggests the change happened as early as v2.0 and as late as v3.0.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Since its original release for the Amiga, Vim has been ported to many environments including Atari MiNT, BeOS, MS-DOS, Windows starting from Windows NT 3.1, OS/2, OS/390, MorphOS, OpenVMS, QNX, RISC OS, Linux, BSD, and Classic Mac OS.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Independent ports of Vim are available for Android and iOS.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim has been and continues to be popular for software development.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] In 2018, it was voted the most popular editor amongst *Linux Journal* readers.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] In 2015, the Stack Overflow developer survey found it to be the third most popular text editor, and, in 2019, the fifth most popular development environment.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] In 1988, Bram Moolenaar began work on what would become Vim.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] He used the codebase for the Stevie editor ported to Amiga (by Tony Andrews et al.) as a starting point.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Version 1.14 (completed 2 November 1991) became the first public release.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] It was distributed via Fish Disk #591 in January 1992.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim is released under the Vim license, which includes some charityware clauses that encourage users who enjoy the software to consider donating to children in Uganda.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] The Vim license is compatible with the GNU General Public License through a special clause allowing distribution of modified copies under the GNU GPL version 2.0 or later.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Building upon the core vi functionality, Vim provides a user experience that integrates keyboard-entered command input with a full-screen editing experience.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim allows a user with a typical keyboard to keep their fingers on the home row, which can be an advantage for touch typing.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Via its GUI mode (called gVim), it presents an interface with a more modern experience including aspects such as menus, toolbars and icons.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] The full functionality is still expressed through its command line mode.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim has a built-in help facility accessible via the `:help` command.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] The Vim tutorial for beginners, called vimtutor, is usually installed alongside Vim, but is a separate executable and can be run separately.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] The Vim Users' Manual details Vim's features and can be read from within Vim, or found online.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim features various special memory entries called registers (not to be confused with hardware or processor registers).
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] When cutting, deleting, copying, or pasting text the user can choose to store the manipulated text in a register.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] There are 36 general-purpose registers associated with letters and numbers ([a-z0-9]) and a range of special ones that either contain special values (current filename, last command, etc.) or serve a special purpose.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Like vi, Vim supports multiple editing modes.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Depending on the mode, entered characters are either processed as command input or inserted as text.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim is customizable and extensible, making it attractive to those who want control and flexibility in a text editing environment.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Users can execute complex commands with *key bindings*, which can be customized and extended.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] The *recording* feature allows for the creation of macros to automate sequences of keystrokes and call internal or user-defined functions and mappings.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Abbreviations, similar to macros and key mappings, facilitate the expansion of short strings of text into longer ones and can also be used to correct mistakes.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim also features an *easy* mode for users wanting a simpler user experience.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] There are many plugins available that extend or add new functionality to Vim.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] These plugins are usually written in Vim's internal scripting language, vimscript (also known as VimL), but can be written in other languages as well.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] There are projects bundling together complex scripts and customizations and aimed at turning Vim into a tool for a specific task or adding a major flavour to its behaviour.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Examples include Cream, which makes Vim behave like a click-and-type editor, or VimOutliner, which provides a comfortable outliner for users of Unix-like systems.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim provides many features beyond what vi provides.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim continually saves information to a file that allows for recovering from a crash.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Generally, the file extension is ".swp", but if the user tries to open a file when the recovery file already exists, then Vim notifies the user of the condition.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] If the user confirms to proceed, Vim uses a different extension to form a name for a file that does not exist.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] The extensions are along the progression: ".swo", ".swn", ".swm", etc.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim provides a vi-compatibility mode that limits its functionality to be similar to that of vi.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] However, even in compatibility mode, Vim is not entirely compatible with vi as specified by POSIX.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] For example, Vim does not support vi's open mode.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim's developers state that it is "very much compatible with Vi".
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Version 9.0 added **Vim9 script**, a new script language closer to commonly used languages.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim macros can contain a sequence of *normal-mode* commands, but can also invoke ex commands or functions written in Vim script for more complex tasks.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Almost all extensions (called plugins or more commonly scripts) of the core Vim functionality are written in Vim script, but plugins can also utilize other languages like Perl, Python, Lua, Ruby, Tcl, or Racket.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] These plugins can be installed manually, or through a plugin manager such as Vundle, Pathogen, or Vim-Plug.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] Vim script files are stored as plain text, similarly to other code, and the filename extension is usually `.vim`.
[src:vimscript-deep/vim-text-editor] One notable exception to that is Vim's config file, `.vimrc`.
